ce:section.ce:para:
To comprehensively evaluate the separation performance of the as-prepared monolithic columns, nine types of neutral and charged compounds with varying structures and properties were selected as the target analytes, including alkylbenzenes, methylbenzenes, substituted benzenes, halobenzenes, chlorobenzenes, PAHs, hydroxybenzoates, aromatic amines and phenolic compounds. Under optimal separation conditions, all analytes were baseline separated using 8N2OH-CDs-poly(GMA-EDMA) monoliths (Fig. 4
                        ). Under the same conditions, DHN-CDs-poly(GMA-co-EDMA) also achieved baseline separation for six analytes, whereas poly(GMA-co-EDMA) failed to achieve baseline separation for any of them. Furthermore, a comparative analysis was further conducted to evaluate the separation performance of our CDs-incorporated monolithic columns against previously reported nanomaterial-modified columns for nano/capillary HPLC [54–59]. As summarized in Table 1
                        , the CDs-based monolithic columns exhibited superior chromatographic efficiency and/or selectivity, demonstrating their exceptional potential as high-performance and robust stationary phases for microcolumn LC applications. These findings clearly demonstrate the crucial role of the incorporated 8N2OH-CDs and DHN-CDs in significantly enhancing the separation selectivity and applicability of the polymer monoliths. According to the log Ko/w values (Table S3), the elution order of all neutral analytes was correlated with their hydrophobicity. The results confirmed that the strong hydrophobic interaction between CDs-poly(GMA-EDMA) column and analytes played a significant role in the separation process. Furthermore, the 8N2OH-CDs-poly(GMA-EDMA) column exhibited superior separation selectivity for the tested analytes compared to the DHN-CDs-poly(GMA-co-EDMA) column, consistent with the relative hydrophobicity of the two types of CDs. These observations collectively highlight the importance of hydrophobic interactions between the analytes and the incorporated CDs in improving separation selectivity.
